# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-general-history-of-the-pyrates] Its author uses the name Captain Charles Johnson, generally considered a pen name for one of London's writer-publishers.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-general-history-of-the-pyrates] The book also contains the first recorded use of the name Jolly Roger for the pirate flag, and shows the skull and crossbones design.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-general-history-of-the-pyrates] It is not considered a reliable historical source by many modern scholars and academics of pirate history, essentially being fan fiction.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-general-history-of-the-pyrates] First appearing in Charles Rivington's shop in London, the book sold so well that by 1726 an enlarged fourth edition had appeared.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-general-history-of-the-pyrates] It pandered to the British public's taste for the exotic; revelling in graphic stories on the high seas.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-general-history-of-the-pyrates] English naval historian David Cordingly writes: "It has been said, and there seems no reason to question this, that Captain Johnson created the modern conception of pirates." Scottish novelists Robert Louis Stevenson (author of *Treasure Island*) and J.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-general-history-of-the-pyrates] Barrie (author of *Peter Pan* featuring Captain Hook) both identified Johnson's *General History of the Pyrates* as one of their major influences, and Stevenson even borrowed one character's name (Israel Hands) from a list of Blackbeard's crew which appeared in Johnson's book.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-general-history-of-the-pyrates] The author, who uses the name Captain Charles Johnson, has remained unknown in spite of numerous attempts by historians to discover their identity.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-general-history-of-the-pyrates] In 1932, literary scholar John Robert Moore argued that Daniel Defoe was the true author of *A General History*.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-general-history-of-the-pyrates] Other sources, including a 2004 paper, suggest that the author could have been publisher Nathaniel Mist, or somebody working for Mist.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-general-history-of-the-pyrates] Author Colin Woodard, in *The Republic of Pirates*, considers attribution of Johnson's work to Defoe to be erroneous, and prefers the hypothesis that Johnson was Mist.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-general-history-of-the-pyrates] Other hypotheses include multiple writers including Mist being involved in the construction of the book.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-general-history-of-the-pyrates] The first mostly deals with early 18th-century pirates, while Volume II records the exploits of their predecessors a few decades earlier.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-general-history-of-the-pyrates] In the first volume, the author sticks fairly close to the available sources, though the author embellishes the stories somewhat.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-general-history-of-the-pyrates] The author stretches the truth farther in the second volume and includes the biographies of three subjects who may be entirely fictional.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-general-history-of-the-pyrates] The book has been hugely influential in shaping popular notions of piracy.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-general-history-of-the-pyrates] as well as biographies of the probably fictional captains James Misson, William Lewis, and John Cornelius.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-journal-of-the-plague-year] Presented as an eyewitness account of the events at the time, it was written in the years just prior to the book's first publication in March 1722.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-journal-of-the-plague-year] Defoe was only five years old in 1665 when the Great Plague took place, and the book itself was published under the initials *H.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-journal-of-the-plague-year] F.* and is probably based on the journals of Defoe's uncle, Henry Foe, who, like 'H.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-journal-of-the-plague-year] F.', was a saddler who lived in the Whitechapel district of East London.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-journal-of-the-plague-year] In the book, Defoe goes to great pains to achieve an effect of verisimilitude, identifying specific neighbourhoods, streets, and even houses in which events took place.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-journal-of-the-plague-year] Additionally, it provides tables of casualty figures and discusses the credibility of various accounts and anecdotes received by the narrator.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-journal-of-the-plague-year] The book is often compared to the actual, contemporary accounts of the plague in the diary of Samuel Pepys.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-journal-of-the-plague-year] Defoe's account, which appears to include much research, is far more systematic and detailed than Pepys's first-person account.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-journal-of-the-plague-year] How the *Journal* is to be classified has been disputed.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-journal-of-the-plague-year] It was initially presented and read as a work of nonfiction, but by the 1780s the work's fictional status was accepted.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-journal-of-the-plague-year] Debate continued as to whether Defoe could be regarded as the work's author rather than merely its editor.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-journal-of-the-plague-year] Edward Wedlake Brayley wrote in 1835 that the *Journal* is "emphatically, not a fiction, not based on fiction ... great injustice is done to [Defoe's] memory so to represent it." Brayley takes pains to compare Defoe's account with known *bona fide* accounts such as *Loimologia* by Dr.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-journal-of-the-plague-year] Nathaniel Hodges (1672), the diary of Samuel Pepys, and Thomas Vincent's *God's Terrible Voice in the City by Plague and Fire* (1667), as well as primary sources.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-journal-of-the-plague-year] Other literary critics have argued that the work should be regarded as a work of imaginative fiction, and thus can justifiably be described as an "historical novel".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-journal-of-the-plague-year] Walter George Bell, a historian of the plague, noted that Defoe should not be considered to be a historian because he uses his sources uncritically.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-journal-of-the-plague-year] These alternative conceptualisations of the *Journal* – as fiction, history, or history-cum-fiction – continue to exist.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-journal-of-the-plague-year] References to the book's title have been made in Michael D.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-journal-of-the-plague-year] A comparison of plague-driven behaviour described by Defoe and the COVID-19 crisis of 2020 is discussed in "Persistent Patterns of Behavior: Two Infectious Disease Outbreaks 350 Years Apart", an article in the journal *Economic Inquiry*, and also in a commentary in *The Guardian*.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-journal-of-the-plague-year] The 1975 play *A Journal of the Plague Year* by Shūji Terayama in collaboration with Rio Kishida is inspired by the work, and deals with the effects of a plague in a town in Southeast Asia.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain] The *Tour* is roughly divided into several tours, or circuits, around Britain.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain] The first two, through Essex, Colchester, Harwich, Suffolk, Norfolk, and Cambridgeshire, and through the Kent Coast, Maidstone, Canterbury, Sussex, Hampshire, and Surrey, are complete circuits, both beginning and ending in London.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain] Letter 3 describes a journey out to Land's End, while Letter 4 starts Volume 2 with the journey back.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain] Letter 5 focuses on London and the Court.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain] Volume 2 ends with Letters 6 and 7 describing a path out to Anglesey and back.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain] Finally, in Volume 3, the narrator begins at the Trent or the Mersey and slowly travels northwards from the Midlands, taking up Letters 8 through 10.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain] Scotland is divided into three convenient units for Letters 11 through 13.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain] Following the first edition, printed between 1724 and 1727, the *Tour* was published several more times.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain] A decade after the original printing, printer and future novelist Samuel Richardson secured the rights and printed the second edition of the *Tour*, releasing an edition with substantial revisions on 13 October 1738.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain] He was responsible for at least some of the revisions in this edition, as well as in the subsequent editions of 1742, 1748, 1753, and 1761–62.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain] Richardson's biographers comment that a "travel book seems an odd thing for Richardson to have worked on, since few men were less travelled," and note that, "as it is revised [by Richardson], the *Tour* becomes less and less like a travel book".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/an-essay-upon-projects] The text was written in 1693 and published in 1697.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/an-essay-upon-projects] The title page states that it was "[p]rinted by R.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/an-essay-upon-projects] R. for Tho[mas] Cockerill, at the Three Legs in the Poultrey.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/an-essay-upon-projects] MDCXCVII." There is no known manuscript of the work.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/an-essay-upon-projects] The essay was reprinted several times and reached a wide audience.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/an-essay-upon-projects] Many of its issues were later revised in a series of pamphlets which were published under the nom-de-plume of Andrew Moreton.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/an-essay-upon-projects] They are titled *Every-body's Business, Is No-body's Business* (1725), *The Protestant Monastery* (1726), *Parochial Tyranny* (1727), *Augusta Triumphans* (1728) and *Second Thoughts are Best* (1729).
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/an-essay-upon-projects] Compared to these works, however, *An Essay Upon Projects* is more focused on moral criticism than being project-oriented.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The Isle of Anglesey (including Holy Island) has an area of 275 square miles (712 km2) and had a population of 69,097 in 2024.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] After Holyhead, located on Holy Island, the largest settlements are Llangefni in the centre of Anglesey and Amlwch on the northern coast.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The economy of the county is mostly based on agriculture, energy, and tourism, the latter especially on the coast.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Holyhead is also a major ferry port for Dublin, Ireland.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The county has the second-highest percentage of Welsh speakers in Wales, at 57.2%, and is considered a heartland of the language.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The Isle of Anglesey is part of the preserved county of Gwynedd.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The island of Anglesey, (excluding Holy Island) at 261 square miles (676 km2), is the largest in Wales and the Irish Sea and the seventh largest in Britain.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The northern and eastern coasts of the island are rugged, and the southern and western coasts are generally gentler; the interior is gently undulating.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] In the north of the island is Llyn Alaw, a reservoir with an area of 1.4 square miles (4 km2), which supplies drinking water to the northern half of the island.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Holy Island, located off the west coast of Anglesey, has a similar landscape, with a rugged north and west coast and beaches to the east and south.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The two larger islands are surrounded by smaller islands; several, including South Stack and Puffin Island, are home to seabird colonies.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Large parts of the county's coastline have been designated an Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Since 2015 the whole county has been designated as a UNESCO Global Geopark for its unique and wide-ranging geology.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The county has many prehistoric monuments, such as Bryn Celli Ddu burial chamber.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The medieval House of Aberffraw, which ruled the Kingdom of Gwynedd until 1283, originated on Anglesey and maintained courts on the island at (*llysoedd*) at Aberffraw and Rhosyr.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] After the Conquest of Wales by Edward I, Beaumaris Castle was constructed at the south-eastern corner of Anglesey; today it is part of the Castles and Town Walls of King Edward in Gwynedd World Heritage Site.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] During the nineteenth century the Menai Strait to the mainland was spanned by two bridges: the Menai Suspension Bridge, designed by Thomas Telford in 1826, and the Britannia Bridge, originally designed by Robert Stephenson in 1850.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The English name for Anglesey might be derived from the Old Norse, either *Ǫngullsey* "Hook Island" or *Ǫnglisey* "Ǫngli's Island".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] No record of such an Ǫngli survives, but the place name was used by Viking raiders as early as the 10th century and later adopted by the Normans during their invasions of Gwynedd.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The traditional folk etymology reading the name as the "Island of the Angles (English)" may account for its Norman use but has no merit; the Angles' name itself is probably cognate with the shape of the Angeln peninsula.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] All of them ultimately derive from the proposed Proto-Indo-European root **ank-* ("to flex, bend, angle").
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Throughout the 18th and 19th centuries and into the 20th, it was usually spelt **Anglesea** in documents, a spelling that is still occasionally used today.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The name is probably cognate with the Gaelic name of the Isle of Man, *Mannin* (*Manaw* in Welsh), usually derived from a Celtic word for 'mountain' (reflected in Welsh *mynydd*, Breton *menez* and Scottish Gaelic *monadh*), from a Proto-Celtic **moniyos*.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The history of the settlement of the local people of Anglesey starts in the Mesolithic period.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Anglesey and Great Britain were uninhabitable until after the previous ice age.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] It was not until 12,000 years ago that the island of Great Britain became hospitable.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The oldest excavated sites on Anglesey include *Trwyn Du* (Welsh: *Black nose*) at Aberffraw.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The Mesolithic site located at Aberffraw Bay (Porth Terfyn) was buried underneath a Bronze Age 'kerb cairn' which was constructed c.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The bowl barrow (kerb cairn) covered a material deposited from the early Mesolithic period; the archeological find dates to 7000 BC.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] After millennia of hunter-gather civilisation in the British Isles, the first villages were constructed from 4000 BC.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Neolithic settlements were built in the form of long houses, on Anglesey is one of the first villages in Wales, it was built at Llanfaethlu.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Also an example permanent settlement on Anglesey is of a Bronze Age built burial mound, Bryn Celli Ddu (English: Dark Grove Hill).
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The mound started as a henge enclosure around 3000 BC and was adapted several times over a millennium.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] There are numerous megalithic monuments and menhirs in the county, testifying to the presence of humans in prehistory.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Plas Newydd is near one of 28 cromlechs that remain on uplands overlooking the sea.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The Welsh Triads claim that the island of Anglesey was once part of the mainland.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] After the Neolithic age, the Bronze Age began (c.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Some sites were continually used for thousands of years from original henge enclosures, then during the Iron Age, and also some of these sites were later adapted by Celts into hillforts and finally were in use during the Roman period (c.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Castell Bryn Gwyn (English: White hill castle, also called *Bryn Beddau*, or the "hill of graves") near Llanidan, Anglesey is an example of a Neolithic site that became a hillfort that was used until the Roman period by the Ordovices, the local tribe who were defeated in battle by a Roman legion (c.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Bronze Age monuments were also built throughout the British Isles.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] During this period, the *Mynydd Bach* cairn in South-west Anglesey was being used.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] It is a Beaker period prehistoric funerary monument.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] During the Iron Age the Celts built dwellings huts, also known as roundhouses.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] These were established near the previous settlements.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Some huts with walled enclosures were discovered on the banks of the river (Welsh: *afon*) Gwna near.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] An example of a well-preserved hut circle is over the Cymyran Strait on Holy Island.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The Holyhead Mountain Hut Circles (Welsh: *Tŷ Mawr / Cytiau'r Gwyddelod*, Big house / "Irishmen's Huts") were inhabited by ancient Celts and were first occupied before the Iron Age, c.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The Anglesey Iron Age began after 500 BC.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Archeological research discovered limpet shells which were found from 200 BC on a wall at Tŷ Mawr and Roman-era pottery from the 3rd to 4th centuries AD.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Some of these huts were still being used for agricultural purposes as late as the 6th century.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The first excavation of Ty Mawr was conducted by William Owen Stanley of Penrhos, Anglesey (son of Baron Stanley of Alderley).
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Historically, Anglesey has long been associated with the druids.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The Roman conquest of Anglesey began in 60 AD when the Roman general Gaius Suetonius Paulinus, determined to break the power of the druids, attacked the island using his amphibious Batavian contingent as a surprise vanguard assault and then destroyed the shrine and the nemeta (sacred groves).
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] News of Boudica's revolt reached him just after his victory, causing him to withdraw his army before consolidating his conquest.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The island was finally brought into the Roman Empire by Gnaeus Julius Agricola, the Roman governor of Britain, in 78 AD.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] During the Roman occupation, the area was notable for the mining of copper.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The foundations of Caer Gybi, a fort in Holyhead, are Roman, and the present road from Holyhead to Llanfairpwllgwyngyll was originally a Roman road.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The island was grouped by Ptolemy with Ireland ("Hibernia") rather than with Britain ("Albion").
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] After the Roman departure from Britain in the early 5th century, pirates from Ireland colonised Anglesey and the nearby Llŷn Peninsula.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] In response to this, Cunedda ap Edern, a Gododdin warlord from Scotland, came to the area and began to drive the Irish out.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] This was continued by his son Einion Yrth ap Cunedda and grandson Cadwallon Lawhir ap Einion; the last Irish invaders were finally defeated in battle in 470.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] During the 9th century, King Rhodri Mawr unified Wales and separated the country into at least 3 provinces between his sons.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] He gave Gwynedd to his son, Anarawd ap Rhodri, who founded the medieval Welsh dynasty, The House of Aberffraw on Anglesey.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The island had a good defensive position, and so Aberffraw became the site of the royal court (Welsh: *Llys*) of the Kingdom of Gwynedd.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Apart from devastating Danish raids in 853 and 968 in Aberffraw, it remained the capital until the 13th, after Rhodri Mawr had moved his family seat from Caernarfon and built a royal palace at Aberffraw in 873.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] This is when improvements to the English navy made the location indefensible.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Anglesey was also briefly the most southerly possession of the Norwegian Empire.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] After the Irish, the island was invaded by Vikings—some raids were noted in famous sagas (see Menai Strait History) such as the Jómsvíkinga—and by Saxons, and Normans, before falling to Edward I of England in the 13th century.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The connection with the Vikings can be seen in the name of the island.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] In ancient times it was called "Maenige" and received the name "Ongulsey" or Angelsoen, from where the current name originates.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Anglesey (with Holy Island) is one of the 13 historic counties of Wales.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] In medieval times, before the conquest of Wales in 1283, *Môn* often had periods of temporary independence, when frequently bequeathed to the heirs of kings as a sub-kingdom of Gwynedd, an example of this was *Llywelyn ap Iorwerth* (Llywelyn I, the Great c.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] 1200s) who was styled the *Prince of Aberffraw*.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] After the Norman invasion of Wales was one of the last times this occurred a few years after 1171, after the death of Owain Gwynedd, when the island was inherited by Rhodri ab Owain Gwynedd, and between 1246 and about 1255 when it was granted to Owain Goch as his share of the kingdom.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] After the conquest of Wales by Edward I, Anglesey became a county under the terms of the Statute of Rhuddlan of 1284.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Hitherto it had been divided into the *cantrefi* of Aberffraw, Rhosyr and Cemaes.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] During 1294 as a rebellion of the former house of Aberffraw, Prince Madog ap Llywelyn had attacked King Edward I's castles in North Wales.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] As a direct response, Beaumaris Castle was constructed to control Edward's interests in Anglesey, but by the 1320s the build was abandoned and never complete.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The castle was besieged by Owain Glyndŵr in the early 15th century.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] It was ruinous by 1609; however, the 6th Viscount Bulkeley purchased the castle from the Crown in 1807 and it has been open to the public under the guardianship of the Crown ever since 1925.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Due to its geographic proximity, Anglesey (and particularly Holyhead) enjoyed close cultural ties with Ireland throughout the later parts of this period.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] A 2023 study in *The Welsh History Review* by historian Adam N.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Coward highlights the interconnectedness of landed gentry families in Ireland and Anglesey between the 17th and 20th centuries, with connections ranging from close geographical proximity and shared transport networks to marriage and family ties.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] One example, the article notes, is that in 1663 the Duke of Ormonde wrote from Dublin Castle to Lord Bulkley of Baron Hill, Anglesey, who had been created Viscount Bulkeley of Cashel in 1644, about bringing partridges from Anglesey to Ireland for a hunt.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The Shire Hall in Llangefni was completed in 1899.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] During the First World War, the Presbyterian minister and celebrity preacher, John Williams, toured the island as part of an effort to recruit young men as volunteers.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The island's location made it ideal for monitoring German U-Boats in the Irish Sea, with half a dozen airships based at Mona.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] By the end of the war, some 1,000 of the island's men had died on active service.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] In 1936 the NSPCC opened its first branch on Anglesey.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] During the Second World War, Anglesey received Italian POWs.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The island was designated a reception zone, and was home to evacuee children from Liverpool and Manchester.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] In 1971, a 100,000 ton per annum aluminum smelter was opened by Rio Tinto Zinc Corporation and British Insulated Callender's Cables with Kaiser Aluminum and Chemical Corporation as a 30 per cent partner.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] In 1974, Anglesey became a district of the new county of Gwynedd known under the name “Anglesey-Ynys Môn”.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Until 1974, Anglesey was divided into civil parishes for the purpose of local government; these in large part equated to ecclesiastical parishes (see the table below), most of which still exist as part of the Church in Wales.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The Local Government (Wales) Act 1994 abolished the 1974 county and the five districts on 1 April 1996, and Anglesey became a separate unitary authority.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] In 2011, the Welsh Government appointed a panel of commissioners to administer the council, which meant the elected members were not in control.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The commissioners remained until an election was held in May 2013, restoring an elected Council.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Before the period of direct administration, there had been a majority of independent councillors.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Though members did not generally divide along party lines, these were organised into five non-partisan groups on the council, containing a mix of party and independent candidates.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The position has been similar since the election, although the Labour Party has formed a governing coalition with the independents.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Brand new council offices were built at Llangefni in the 1990s for the new Isle of Anglesey County Council.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Anglesey is a low-lying island with low hills spaced evenly over the north.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The highest six are Holyhead Mountain, 220 metres (720 ft); Mynydd Bodafon, 178 metres (584 ft); Mynydd Eilian, 177 metres (581 ft); Mynydd y Garn, 170 metres (560 ft); Bwrdd Arthur, 164 metres (538 ft); and Mynydd Llwydiarth, 158 metres (518 ft).
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] To the south and south-east, the island is divided from the Welsh mainland by the Menai Strait, which at its narrowest point is about 250 metres (270 yd) wide.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] In all other directions the island is surrounded by the Irish Sea.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] At 676 km2 (261 sq mi), it is the 52nd largest island of Europe and just five km2 (1.9 sq mi) smaller than the main island of Singapore.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] There are a few natural lakes, mostly in the west, such as Llyn Llywenan, the largest on the island, Llyn Coron, and Cors Cerrig y Daran, but rivers are few and small.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] There are two large water supply reservoirs operated by Welsh Water.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] These are Llyn Alaw to the north of the island and Llyn Cefni in the centre of the island, which is fed by the headwaters of the Afon Cefni.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The climate is humid (though less so than neighbouring mountainous Gwynedd) and generally equable thanks to the Gulf Stream.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The land is of variable quality and has probably lost some fertility.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Anglesey has the northernmost olive grove in Europe and presumably in the world.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The coast of the Isle of Anglesey is more populous than the interior.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The largest community is Holyhead, which is located on Holy Island and had a population of 12,103 at the 2021 United Kingdom census.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] It is followed by Amlwch (3,697), Llanfair-Mathafarn-Eithaf (3,085), and Menai Bridge (3,046), all located on the coast of the island of Anglesey.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The largest community in the interior of Anglesey is Llangefni (5,500), the county town; the next-largest is Llanfihangel Ysgeifiog (1,711).
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Beaumaris (Welsh: *Biwmares*) in the east features Beaumaris Castle, built by Edward I during his Bastide campaign in North Wales.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Beaumaris is a yachting centre, with boats moored in the bay or off Gallows Point.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The village of Newborough (Welsh: *Niwbwrch*), in the south, created when townsfolk of Llanfaes were relocated for the building of Beaumaris Castle, includes the site of Llys Rhosyr, another court of medieval Welsh princes featuring one of the United Kingdom's oldest courtrooms.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The centrally located Llangefni is the island's administrative centre.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The town of Menai Bridge (Welsh: *Porthaethwy*) in the south-east, expanded to accommodate workers and construction when the first bridge to the mainland was being built.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Hitherto Porthaethwy had been one of the main ferry ports for the mainland.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] A short distance from the town lies Bryn Celli Ddu, a Stone Age burial mound.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Nearby is the village with the longest name in Europe, Llanfairpwllgwyngyllgogerychwyrndrobwllllantysiliogogogoch, and Plas Newydd, ancestral home of the Marquesses of Anglesey.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The town of Amlwch lies in the north-east of the island and was once largely industrialised, having grown in the 18th century to support a major copper-mining industry at Parys Mountain.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Other settlements include Cemaes, Pentraeth, Gaerwen, Dwyran, Bodedern, Malltraeth and Rhosneigr.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The coastline is classed as an Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty, with many sandy beaches, notably along its east coast between Beaumaris and Amlwch and west coast from Ynys Llanddwyn through Rhosneigr to the bays around Carmel Head.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The north coast has sharp cliffs with small bays.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Anglesey Coastal Path outlining the island is 124 miles (200 km) long and touches 20 towns and villages.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The starting point is St Cybi's Church, Holyhead.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Tourism is now the major economic activity.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Agriculture comes second, with local dairies being some of the most productive in the region.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Major industry is restricted to Holyhead (Caergybi), which until 30 September 2009 supported an aluminium smelter, and the Amlwch area, once a copper mining town.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Nearby stood Wylfa Nuclear Power Station and a former bromine extraction plant.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] With construction starting in 1963, the two Wylfa reactors began producing power in 1971.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] One reactor was decommissioned in 2012, the other in 2015.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] There were plans to install tidal-flow turbines near The Skerries off the north coast, and for a major biomass plant on Holy Island (Ynys Gybi).
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Developing such low-carbon-energy assets to their full potential forms part of the Anglesey Energy Island project.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] When the aluminium smelter closed in September 2009, it cut its workforce from 450 to 80, in a major blow to the island's economy, especially to Holyhead.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The Royal Air Force station RAF Valley (Y Fali) holds the RAF Fast Jet Training School and 22 Sqn Search and Rescue Helicopters, both units providing employment to about 500 civilians.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] RAF Valley is now the 22 Sqn Search and Rescue headquarters.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The range of smaller industries is mostly in industrial and business parks such as Llangefni and Gaerwen.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The island is on one of the main road routes from Britain to Ireland, via ferries from Holyhead on Holy Island to Dún Laoghaire and Dublin Port.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The Anglesey Sea Zoo is a local attraction offering looks at local marine wildlife from common lobsters to congers.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] All fish and crustaceans on display are caught round the island and placed in habitat reconstructions.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The zoo also breeds lobsters commercially for food and oysters for pearls, both from local stocks.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Sea salt (*Halen Môn*, from local sea water) is produced in a facility nearby, having formerly been made at the Sea Zoo site.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Plans were offered in 2013 by Horizon, a subsidiary of Hitachi, to start production in the 2020s.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Though enthusiastically endorsed by Anglesey Council and Welsh Assembly members, protesters raised doubts about its economic and safety claims, and in January 2019 Hitachi announced it was putting development on hold.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] On 17 January 2019, Hitachi-Horizon Nuclear Power announced it was abandoning plans to build a nuclear plant on the Wylfa Newydd site in Anglesey.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] There had been concern that the start might have involved too much public expenditure, but Hitachi-Horizon say the decision to scrap has cost the company over £2 billion.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Much of Anglesey is used for relatively intensive cattle and sheep farming, but several important wetland sites have protected status and the lakes all have significant ecological interest, including a wide range of aquatic and semi-aquatic bird species.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] In the west, the Malltraeth Marshes are believed to support an occasional visiting bittern, and the nearby estuary of the Afon Cefni has a bird population made famous internationally by the paintings of Charles Tunnicliffe, who lived and died at Malltraeth on the Cefni estuary.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The RAF airstrip at Mona is a nesting site for skylarks.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The sheer cliff faces at South Stack near Holyhead provide nesting sites for large numbers of auks, including puffins, razorbills and guillemots, along with choughs and peregrine falcons.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Anglesey holds several tern species, including the roseate tern on three breeding sites – see Anglesey tern colonies.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] There are marked occurrences of the *Juncus subnodulosus*–*Cirsium palustre* fen-meadow plant association marked by hydrophilic grasses, sedges and forbs.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Anglesey supports two of the UK's remnant colonies of red squirrels, at Pentraeth and Newborough.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Almost the whole coastline of Anglesey is designated as an Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty (AONB) to protect the aesthetic appeal and variety of the island's coastal landscape and habitats from inappropriate development.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The coastal zone of Anglesey was classed as an AONB in 1966 and confirmed as such in 1967.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The AONB is predominantly coastal, covering most of Anglesey's 125 miles (201 km) coastline, but includes Holyhead Mountain and Mynydd Bodafon.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Large areas of other land protected by the AONB form the backdrop to the coast.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The AONB is about 221 sq. m (85 sq mi) and is the largest in Wales, covering a third of the island.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] A number of Anglesey habitats gain still greater protection through UK and European designations of their nature conservation value.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] These support a variety of wildlife, such as harbour porpoises and marsh fritillary.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The AONB takes in three sections of open, undeveloped coastline designated as Heritage Coast.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] These non-statutory designations complement the AONB and cover about 31 miles (50 km) of the coastline.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Popular recreations include sailing, angling, cycling, walking, wind surfing and jet skiing.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] They place pressures and demands on the AONB, while stoking the local economy.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] It belongs to the International Island Games Association.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Anglesey's biggest successes were at the 1997 Island Games in Jersey, (11th in the medals table, with two gold, three silver and nine bronze medals) and the 2005 Island Games in the Shetland Islands, (again 11th, with 4 gold, 2 silver and 2 bronze).
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The annual Anglesey Show is held on the second Tuesday and Wednesday of August.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Farmers from around the country compete in livestock–rearing contests, including sheep and cattle.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Other events include Gottwood, an electronic music and arts festival held each summer at the Carreglwyd estate.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Môn FM, a volunteer community radio station, broadcasts across the island from the county town, Llangefni, and also covers northern Gwynedd.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Capital Anglesey & Gwynedd, a commercial contemporary hit radio station, broadcasts local news bulletins.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] In 2017 filming took place for the Netflix TV series *Free Rein*.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Locations included Newborough Warren and Beaumaris Pier.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] In 2018, the BBC began a three-part series entitled *Anglesey: Island Lives*, detailing the lives of several residents of the island.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] In the first episode, Kris Hughes, a noted companion of the Druid community and the Anglesey Druid Order, was followed as the order marked the Summer Solstice.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Anglesey is a stronghold of the Welsh language.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] According to the 2011 census it was the local authority with the second highest proportion of Welsh speakers.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Today, Welsh is less widely used, but remains the dominant language in some areas, particularly in the centre, including Llangefni and some parts of the south coast.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The geology of Anglesey is complex and frequently targeted for geology field trips by schools and colleges.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] These rocks are schists and phyllites, often contorted and disturbed.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The general line of strike of the formations in the island is from north-east to south-west.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] A belt of granitic rocks lies just north-west of the central Precambrian mass, reaching from Llanfaelog near the coast to the vicinity of Llanerchymedd.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Between this granite and the Precambrian of Holyhead is a narrow tract of Ordovician slates and grits with Llandovery beds in places, spreading out in the north of the island between Dulas Bay and Carmel Point.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] A small patch of Ordovician strata lies on the northern side of Beaumaris.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] In parts, these Ordovician rocks are much folded, crushed and metamorphosed, and associated with schists and altered volcanic rocks which are probably Precambrian.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Between the eastern and central Precambrian masses Carboniferous rocks are found.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Carboniferous Limestone occupies a broad area south of Lligwy Bay and Pentraeth, and sends a narrow spur in south-westwards by Llangefni to Malltraeth Sands.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] It is underlain on the north-west by a red basement conglomerate and yellow sandstone (sometimes considered of Old Red Sandstone age).
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Limestone occurs again on the north coast around Llanfihangel and Llangoed; and in the south-west round Llanidan near the Menai Strait.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Puffin Island is made of Carboniferous Limestone.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Malltraeth Marsh is occupied by Coal Measures, and a small patch of the same formation appears near Tal-y-foel Ferry on the Menai Strait.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] A patch of rhyolitic/felsitic rocks forms Parys Mountain, where copper and iron ochre have been worked.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Serpentine (Mona Marble) is found near Llanfair-yn-Neubwll and upon the opposite shore in Holyhead.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Anglesey is the only onshore part of the UK to have sediments dated to the Early Middle Miocene (?Langhian).
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Under the name *GeoMôn*, affirming its extraordinary geological heritage, the island gained membership of the European Geoparks Network in spring 2009. and the Global Geoparks Network in September 2010.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] It has also been designated as a UNESCO Global Geopark since 2015.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] There are 50 primary, all co-educational day schools.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Anglesey is linked to the mainland by the Britannia Bridge, carrying the A55 from Holyhead, and the Menai Suspension Bridge, carrying the A5 trunk road.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The A5025 round the northern edge of Anglesey and the A4080 round the southern edge form a ring.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The North Wales Coast Line travels across the Britannia Bridge to Anglesey.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The six railway stations on the island are Holyhead, Valley, Rhosneigr, Ty Croes, Bodorgan and Llanfairpwll.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Services operated by Avanti West Coast to London Euston, and by Transport for Wales Rail to Chester, Manchester Piccadilly, Birmingham New Street and Cardiff Central.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Historically the island was also served by the Anglesey Central Railway which ran from Gaerwen to Amlwch, and the Red Wharf Bay branch line between Holland Arms railway station and Red Wharf Bay.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Anglesey Airport, until 2020, had a twice-daily scheduled service to Cardiff Airport.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The route was subsidised by the Welsh government and suspended due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] After a 2022 review, the Welsh government announced that it would not reinstate the flights; travel between Cardiff and Anglesey now takes over four hours by road or rail.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The ferry port of Holyhead handles over two million passengers a year.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Stena Line and Irish Ferries sail to Dublin (previously to Dún Laoghaire), forming the main surface transport link from central and northern England and Wales to Ireland.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Anglesey is independently represented in the Island Games (as *Ynys Môn*).
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The team finished joint 17th in the 2009 Games hosted by Åland, winning medals in gymnastics, sailing, and shooting.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Anglesey made an unsuccessful bid for the 2009 games, led by Ynys Môn MP Albert Owen, in the hope of more than £3m of spending if it had hosted the event.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] However, Anglesey lacks two needful facilities: a six-lane competition swimming pool and an athletics track.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Several precursors to the modern football codes were popular in Anglesey.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] They had few rules and were quite violent.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] This arrived in the 1870s and met with local resistance for its perceived associations with drunkenness and rowdiness and the lower classes.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] One critic called it an "un-Christian practice".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] An Anglesey League of teams from Amlwch, Beaumaris, Holyhead, Menai Bridge, Llandegfan, and Llangefni was formed in the 1895–96 season.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] This gave way in 2020 to the North Wales Coast West Football League.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The Ynys Môn football team represents Anglesey at the biannual Island Games, winning gold in 1999.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] In 2018, the island was chosen to host the 2019 Inter Games Football Tournament, where the men's team won gold and the women's team won silver.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] For the aborted 2020–21 season, Llangefni Town and Holyhead Hotspur were due to play in the Cymru North league, the second tier of the Welsh football league system, after winning the Welsh Alliance League two years before.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] There were due to be nine Anglesey sides in the same season's fourth tier North Wales Coast West Football League Premier Division: Aberffraw, Amlwch Town, Bodedern Athletic, Bro Goronwy, Gaerwen, Gwalchmai, Menai Bridge Tigers, Pentraeth and Trearddur Bay Bulls.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] There are a further nine teams in Division One.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Llangefni RFC is the island's highest competing team in the WRU Division One North.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Llangoed hosts an annual rugby sevens contest.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Touring sides have included Manhattan RFC.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Anglesey Hunt, formed in 1757, was the second oldest fox hunting association in Wales after Tivyside Hunt in Cardiganshire.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Every September the Anglesey Festival of Running includes a marathon, a half-marathon, 10-km and 5-km races, and children's contests.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] There are at present no 400-metre, all-weather, synthetic tracks on the island, the nearest being between Bangor and the Britannia Bridge on the mainland.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The Anglesey Circuit (Welsh: Trac Môn) is a licensed MSA and ACU championship racing circuit that opened in 1997.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] It hosts many events all year round and is a popular track.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The Beaumaris Cricket Club formed in 1858.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Clubs at Holyhead, Amlwch and Llangefni formed in the following decade, but not until the 1880s was the sport popular outside the upper classes.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] Bodedern Cricket Club was formed in 1947.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The Royal Anglesey Yacht Club hosts the annual Menai Strait Regatta.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] The Menai Strait hosts two annual open-water contests: the Menai Strait Swim from Foel to Caernarfon (1 mile), and the Pier to Pier Open Water Swim, between Beaumaris and Garth Pier, Bangor.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/anglesey] There is a 25-metre pool at Plas Arthur Leisure Centre in Llangefni.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] As Maximillian Novak points out, Defoe chose a "grand title" for *Augusta Triumphans*.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] It highlights his ambitious aim of making London stand out even at a universal level.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] This city has a significant role in both his biography and work.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Firstly, his travels started and ended in this place.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Secondly, it is "the implicit or explicit setting" of the majority of his writings.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Immediately after this introductory discourse, Andrew Moreton moves on to illustrate the project upon which he has reflected most.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] He fosters the establishment of a London university to oppose the contemporary corruption of learning and education.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Subsequently, four titled sections come one after the other and present other schemes for social improvement.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Section one calls for the establishment of a foundling hospital.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] It would prevent many mothers from freeing themselves of their illegitimate offspring through abortion or abandonment in parishes which do not offer them decent living conditions.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Section two shows how a real academy of music would "prevent the expensive importation of foreign musicians, & c".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Section three firstly offers advice to rescue "youths and servants" from moral corruption.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Secondly, it denounces certain social evils: prostitution, gambling, and a series of dissolute manners to spend one's free time on Sunday such as alcohol misuse.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Thirdly, it makes a digression on husbands's abuses of their wives and comments about contemporary private madhouses.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Section four encourages the adoption of measures to stop street robbery.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] They include moral education and the introduction of a competent and paid body of watchmen as well as an adequate system of street lighting at night.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] The final part of *Augusta Triumphans* is titled "Omissions".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] It is a revision of two aspects of the projects which have been illustrated so far.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Andrew Moreton begins with rejecting his initial idea of founding a London university composed of "only a hall or public room".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Rather, "it should be a large house or inn, in the nature of a college, with store of convenient rooms for gentlemen, not only to study separately, but wherein to lodge their books, for it would be most inconvenient to lug them backwards and forwards".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] He then expands his "discourse on madhouses", particularly by offering a suggestion to impede the unjust confinement of widows or other women who find themselves with a fortune and no male guidance.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] In order to prevent them from becoming victims of greedy and manipulatory "strangers", the nearest male relative should succeed the deceased gentleman in the management of the estate.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] At the end of the pamphlet is attached a letter "To Lieutenant-Colonel Samuel Robinson" which is dated "Sept.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Its signatory, Andrew Moreton, begins with briefly congratulating the addressee for his "election into the chamberlainship of the city of London".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] He subsequently poses a series of questions to understand the purpose of "the orphan's tax".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] The theme of human capability to project is touched upon at the beginning of *Augusta Triumphans* when Andrew Moreton briefly comments on "schemists".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] These figures are mentioned also in *An Essay Upon Projects*.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] In its introduction, the author points out that his country "swarms with [...] a multitude of" planners.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] This project-oriented climate originates from the widespread need to cope with contemporary problems and chaos.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Moreover, since no other age was characterised by such a trend, his epoch could be defined as a "Projecting Age".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Daniel Defoe dealt with "the theme of [...] man's capacity to project" also in *An Essay Upon Projects* (1697) and *Robinson Crusoe* (1719).
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] They respectively are an explicit and an implicit treatment of the same topic.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] In addition to be characterised by opposite approaches, they differ in perspective.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] *An Essay Upon Projects* is socially oriented in that it addresses issues which are of importance for a whole community.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] *Robinson Crusoe*, on the other hand, focuses on the interests of a single human being.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] In *Augusta Triumphans*, Andrew Moreton promotes the foundation of a university, an academy of music and a hospital for foundlings.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] He begins with calling for a university in London and stresses the reasons for making it non-residential.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Firstly, by keep living under the same roof with their families of origin, students are not left to their own devices. and are less likely to fall into temptation.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Young men who are sent to Cambridge or Oxford, on the other hand, waste their time drinking rather than learning themselves.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Secondly, by daily returning to their family's quarter, they contribute to the cultural flourish of London society; they can spread the academic knowledge they acquire through conversation.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Overall, the privileged beneficiary of this plan is the gentry whose residential areas are included in the list of places where Moreton advises establishing colleges: Westminster, St.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] This social group is also invited to finance the whole project "by subscription".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Subsequently, Andrew Moreton urges the establishment of a foundling hospital.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] This would prevent many mothers from getting rid of their illegitimate offspring through abortion or abandoning them in parishes which are incapable of offering them adequate shelter.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] This issue recurs in Defoe's other works, particularly in the novels *Moll Flanders* (1722), *Roxana* (1724), and in the essay *Conjugal Lewdness* (1727).
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] In the early eighteenth century, a large number of abandoned children. were either left on the streets of London or put into the care of parishes.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] However, the latter were not considered reliable.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Some dissipated the money which was supposed to be spent on the support of children; others were accused of entrusting orphans to the care of dishonest nurses selected on the basis of the cheapness of the service they provided.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Lastly, Defoe's fictitious speaker fosters the establishment of an academy of music "to prevent the expensive importation of foreign musicians & c.".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] He points out that the then existing Italian opera, which is financed by upper class lovers of this art, is "improperly called academy" in that it just hires costly foreign musicians.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] It does not encourage the "propagation of science, by training up persons thereto from younger to riper years, under the instruction and inspection of proper artists".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] When *Augusta Triumphans* was published, there existed a joint stock company whose denomination was Royal Academy of Music.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Founded in 1719, it became operative in 1720.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Thanks to governmental subsidies, it could afford to pay salaries which were "beyond the theatre's inherent capacity to pay".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Andrew Moreton encourages the introduction of measures to render servants faithful to their job.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Firstly, they should be offered salaries which are not excessively high.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] In particular, their amount could be set on the basis of their capability of working and managing money.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Secondly, the judicial system should not allow them to resign without just cause.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Lastly, masters ought not to abuse them.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] This scheme aims primarily to keep servants away from idleness and bad company that may lead them into vice and crime.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Eighteenth-century London was populated by a large number of migrants seeking job opportunities.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Being alone and unaware of city dangers, they could easily become pray of unscrupulous people.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Young girls, for instance, could be led into prostitution by manipulative individuals approaching them at their arrival.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Procurers could take the advantage of "the custom of mistresses to meet the wagons which brought country girls to London in order to find and engage servants".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Dorothy George, "the first scene in Hogarth's *Harlot's Progress* was one frequently played in real life".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Andrew Moreton reflects also upon the contemporary system of private madhouses and denounces its inefficiency.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] In the first place, he notices that it allows the institutionalisation of individuals who are affected by no mental disease.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] For instance, they frequently admit healthy wives. confined by abusive husbands for the sole purpose of getting rid of them.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] In the second place, he points out that they do not guarantee adequate treatment of patients in that their staffs neglect or abuse them.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] In the light of this, he suggests substituting them with "licensed madhouses" which are "subject to proper visitation and inspection" and where nobody can be "sent [...] without due reason, inquiry, and authority".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] In the eighteenth century, private madhouses were much discussed.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Nicholas Hervey points out that Defoe was "among the first to question the practice of these institutions in *Augusta Triumphans* (1728)".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] He was late followed by Tobias Smollett who wrote the novel *Sir Lancelot Greaves* (1762). in which the hero of the title criticises unfair detention in madhouses. and reflects upon the difference between sanity and mental illness.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] In 1763, the *Gentleman's Magazine* also denounced the abuse of a series of patients in asylums.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Nicholas Hervey also notices that Defoe "attacked the way husbands were able to confine their wives for the most spurious of reasons".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] This practice was later also denounced by Mary Wollstonecraft in *The Wrongs of Woman* (1798).
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] On this point, Elizabeth Foyster claims that this "was an issue which caused much concern in eighteenth-century England".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Men's right to confine their wives was frequently debated.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] In the essay *At the Limits of Liberty: Married Women and Confinement in eighteenth-century England* (2002), she argues that husbands' detention of their spouses in family dwellings and madhouses had become a new form of conjugal violence.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Her study is based on documents of the King's Bench, the court which held jurisdiction over this issue.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] The last scheme of Andrew Moreton aims to prevent street robbery "first by heavenly, and then by earthly means".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] The former consist in "enforcing and encouraging a reformation of manners, by suppressing of vice and immorality, and punishing profaneness and licentiousness".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Widespread immoral habits are the reading of lustful ballads, swearing, and alcohol abuse.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] The latter include the introduction of an efficient system of surveillance and lighting of the streets.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] First of all, it is necessary to substitute the current inept watch with a body of competent and physically strong men.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] These new guards should carry firearms, swords, and a horn to alert their co-workers.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] They should be assigned to areas which are not too large to be effectively monitored.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] In particular, "no watchman" should "stand above twenty doors distant from his fellow".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Moreover, they ought to be given salaries in recognition of their efforts.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Secondly, streets need to be rendered visible a night.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Therefore, it is important to set up a reasonable number of lamps which are technically capable of providing adequate lighting.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] In this section, Andrew Moreton recalls three peculiar aspects of the culture in Defoe's time.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] The first to be mentioned is the movement for the reformation of manners.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Throughout the 18th-century, large numbers of Englishmen denounced what they saw as the high degree of social immorality and the difficulty of prosecuting victimless offences.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] From 1690 on they gathered and founded a series of societies.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] During the early decades they concentrated on organising and conducting the prosecution of targeted sinners.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] They could take you to court for offences such as drunkenness, swearing, gaming and sodomy.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Later their members shifted their attention to teaching religious and moral values through the delivery of sermons and the production and distribution of pamphlets.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] The second cultural peculiarity is the night watch which existed since the 13th century.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] It consisted of men monitoring the streets during dark hours.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] It had been introduced to favour safety at night together with the enforcement of rules of curfew.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Early criticism about this system date back to the Restoration.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Some of its shortcomings were also reported in the city marshals' accounts of the 1690s.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] They noticed that poor areas could not afford financing this service.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Moreover, watchmen would not carry appropriate weapons and, in some cases, would leave before shift ended.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] In the 1720s, a significant public debate over crime prevention was ongoing and Defoe participated to it through a series of pamphlets.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] In addition to *Augusta Triumphans*, he investigated crime in *Some Considerations Upon Street Walkers* (1726), *Street Robbery Consider'd* (1728), *Second Thoughts Are Best* (1729), and *An Effectual Scheme for the Immediate Preventing of Street Robberies* (1731).
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Lastly, Andrew Moreton deals with street lighting in connection with night watch.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Beattie explains, several changes were made to the urban environment of London for the purpose of improving aspects such as paving and the availability of drinkable water.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Plans were also made to improve street lighting which, compared to other issues, was considered of the utmost importance to prevent crime.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] By rendering places visible to both pedestrians and part-time officers, life was made difficult for felons and this point was highlighted in petitions to Parliament.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] Street lighting eventually became a public system in the City of London through the London Street Lighting Act 1735 (9 Geo.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/augusta-triumphans] It was financed by taxes and provided by private companies.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The county has an area of 3,389 km2 (1,309 sq mi) and had an estimated population of 906,814 in 2022.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Peterborough is in the north-west and the city of Cambridge in the south.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The remainder of the county is rural, and contains the city of Ely in the east, Wisbech in the north-east, and St Neots and Huntingdon in the west.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] For local government purposes Cambridgeshire comprises a non-metropolitan county, with five districts, and the unitary authority area of Peterborough; their local authorities collaborate through Cambridgeshire and Peterborough Combined Authority.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The county did not historically include Huntingdonshire or the Soke of Peterborough, which was part of Northamptonshire.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The north and east of the county are dominated by the Fens, an extremely flat, drained marsh maintained by drainage ditches and dykes; Holme Fen is the UK's lowest physical point, at 2.75 m (9 ft) below sea level.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The flatness of the landscape makes the few areas of higher ground, such as that Ely is built on, very conspicuous.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The landscape in the south and west is gently undulating.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Cambridgeshire's principal rivers are the Nene, which flows through the north of the county and is canalised east of Peterborough; the Great Ouse, which flows from west to east past Huntingdon and Ely; and the Cam, a tributary of the Great Ouse which flows through Cambridge.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Cambridgeshire is noted as the site of Flag Fen in Fengate, one of the earliest-known Neolithic permanent settlements in the United Kingdom, compared in importance to Balbridie in Aberdeen, Scotland.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Must Farm quarry, at Whittlesey, has been described as "Britain's Pompeii due to its relatively good condition, including the 'best-preserved Bronze Age dwellings ever found in the UK'".
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] A great quantity of archaeological finds from the Stone Age, the Bronze Age, and the Iron Age were made in East Cambridgeshire.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The area was settled by the Anglo-Saxons starting in the fifth century.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Genetic testing on seven skeletons found in Anglo-Saxon era graves in Hinxton and Oakington found that five were either migrants or descended from migrants from the continent, one was a native Briton, and one had both continental and native ancestry, suggesting intermarriage.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Cambridgeshire was recorded in the *Domesday Book* as "Grantbridgeshire" (or rather *Grentebriġesċīre*) (related to the river Granta).
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Covering a large part of East Anglia, Cambridgeshire today is the result of several local government unifications.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] In 1965, these two administrative counties were merged to form Cambridgeshire and the Isle of Ely.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Under the Local Government Act 1972 this merged with the county to the west, Huntingdon and Peterborough, which had been formed in 1965, by the merger of Huntingdonshire with the Soke of Peterborough (the latter previously a part of Northamptonshire with its own county council).
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The resulting county was called simply Cambridgeshire.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Since 1998, the City of Peterborough has been separately administered as a unitary authority area.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] It is associated with Cambridgeshire for ceremonial purposes such as Lieutenancy and joint functions such as policing and the fire service.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] In 2002, the conservation charity Plantlife unofficially designated Cambridgeshire's county flower as the Pasqueflower.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The Cambridgeshire Regiment (nicknamed the Fen Tigers), the county-based army unit, fought in the Boer War in South Africa, the First World War and Second World War.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Due to the county's flat terrain and proximity to the continent, during the Second World War the military built many airfields here for RAF Bomber Command, RAF Fighter Command, and the USAAF.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] In recognition of this collaboration, the Cambridge American Cemetery and Memorial is located in Madingley.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Most English counties have nicknames for their people, such as a "Tyke" from Yorkshire and a "Yellowbelly" from Lincolnshire.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The historical nicknames for people from Cambridgeshire are "Cambridgeshire Camel" or "Cambridgeshire Crane", the latter referring to the wildfowl that were once abundant in the Fens.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The term "Fen Tigers" is sometimes used to describe the people who live and work in the Fens.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Cambridgeshire's county flag was selected as an entry from a design competition that ran during 2014.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The design features three golden crowns, two on the top, one on the bottom that are separated by two wavy lines in the middle.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The crowns are meant to represent East Anglia, and the two lines represent the River Cam and are in the Cambridge University's colours.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Large areas of the county are extremely low-lying and Holme Fen is notable for being the UK's lowest physical point at 2.75 m (9 ft) below sea level.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The highest point of the modern administrative county is in the village of Great Chishill at 146 m (480 ft) above sea level.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] However, this parish was historically a part of Essex, having been moved to Cambridgeshire in boundary changes in 1895.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The historic county top is close to the village of Castle Camps where a point on the disused RAF airfield reaches a height of 128 metres (420 ft) above sea level (grid reference TL 63282 41881).
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Other prominent hills are Little Trees Hill and Wandlebury Hill (both at 74 m (243 ft)) in the Gog Magog Hills, Rivey Hill above Linton, Rowley's Hill and the Madingley Hills.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Wicken Fen is a 254.5-hectare (629-acre) biological Site of Special Scientific Interest west of Wicken.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] A large part of it is owned and managed by the National Trust.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The Cambridge Green Belt around the city of Cambridge extends to places such as Waterbeach, Lode, Duxford, Little & Great Abington and other communities a few miles away in nearby districts, to afford a protection from the conurbation.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Cambridgeshire County Council is controlled by the Liberal Democrats, while Peterborough City Council is currently controlled by a Conservative Party minority administration.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] As of 2026, there are four separate proposals for local government in Cambridgeshire and Peterborough to be reorganised into two new unitary authorities, which would replace the existing structure of the county council and six districts (including Peterborough).
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Government consultation on these four proposals ran from 5 February 2026 to 26 March 2026.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] This is a chart of trend of regional gross value added of Cambridgeshire at current basic prices.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The RAF has several stations in the Huntingdon and St Ives area.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] RAF Alconbury, three miles north of Huntingdon, is being reorganised after a period of obsolescence following the departure of the USAF, to be the focus of RAF/USAFE intelligence operations, with activities at Upwood and Molesworth being transferred there.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Close to Cambridge is the so-called Silicon Fen area of high-technology (electronics, computing and biotechnology) companies.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The inland Port of Wisbech on the River Nene is the county's only remaining port.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Cambridgeshire has a comprehensive education system with over 240 state schools, not including sixth form colleges.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The independent sector includes King's Ely and Wisbech Grammar School, founded in 970 and 1379 respectively, they are two of the oldest schools in the country.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Some of the secondary schools act as Village Colleges, institutions unique to Cambridgeshire.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] In addition, Cambridge Regional College and Huntingdonshire Regional College both offer a limited range of higher education courses in conjunction with partner universities.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] These are the settlements in Cambridgeshire with a town charter, city status or a population over 5,000; for a complete list of settlements see list of places in Cambridgeshire.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] See the List of Cambridgeshire settlements by population page for more detail.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The town of Newmarket is surrounded on three sides by Cambridgeshire, being connected by a narrow strip of land to the rest of Suffolk.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Cambridgeshire has seen 32,869 dwellings created from 2002 to 2013 and there are a further 35,360 planned new dwellings between 2016 and 2023.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Cambridgeshire has a maritime temperate climate which is broadly similar to the rest of the United Kingdom, though it is drier than the UK average due to its low altitude and easterly location, the prevailing southwesterly winds having already deposited moisture on higher ground further west.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Average winter temperatures are cooler than the English average, due to Cambridgeshire's inland location and relative nearness to continental Europe, which results in the moderating maritime influence being less strong.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Snowfall is slightly more common than in western areas, due to the relative winter coolness and easterly winds bringing occasional snow from the North Sea.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] In summer temperatures are average or slightly above, due to less cloud cover.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] It reaches 25 °C (77 °F) on around ten days each year, and is comparable to parts of Kent and East Anglia.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Weather station is located 3 miles (4.8 km) from the Cambridge city centre.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Various forms of football have been popular in Cambridgeshire since medieval times at least.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] In 1579 one match played at Chesterton between townspeople and University of Cambridge students ended in a violent brawl that led the Vice-Chancellor to issue a decree forbidding them to play "footeball" outside of college grounds.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] During the nineteenth century, several formulations of the laws of football, known as the Cambridge rules, were created by students at the university.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] One of these codes, dating from 1863, had a significant influence on the creation of the original laws of the Football Association.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Cambridgeshire is also the birthplace of bandy, now an IOC accepted sport.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] According to documents from 1813, Bury Fen Bandy Club was undefeated for 100 years.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] A member of the club, Charles Goodman Tebbutt, wrote down the first official rules in 1882.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Tebbutt was instrumental in spreading the sport to many countries.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Great Britain Bandy Association is based in Cambridgeshire.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Fen skating is a traditional form of skating in the Fenland.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The National Ice Skating Association was set up in Cambridge in 1879, they took the top Fen skaters to the world speedskating championships where James Smart (skater) became world champion.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] On 6–7 June 2015, the inaugural Tour of Cambridgeshire cycle race took place on closed roads across the county.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The event was an official UCI qualification event, and consisted of a Time Trial on the 6th, and a Gran Fondo event on the 7th.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The Gran Fondo event was open to the public, and over 6000 riders took part in the 128 km (80 mi) race.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The River Cam is the main river flowing through Cambridge, parts of the River Nene and River Great Ouse lie within the county.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] In 2021 the latter was used as the course for The Boat Race.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The River Cam serves as the course for the university Lent Bumps and May Bumps and the non-college rowing organised by Cambridgeshire Rowing Association.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] There is only one racecourse in Cambridgeshire, located at Huntingdon.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Cambridge is home to the Kettle's Yard gallery and the artist-run Aid and Abet project space.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Nine miles west of Cambridge next to the village of Bourn is Wysing Arts Centre.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Wisbech has been home to the Wisbech Gallery, South Brink since 2023.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Cambridge Open Studios is the region's large arts organisation with over 500 members.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Every year, more than 370 artists open their doors to visitors during four weekends in July.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The annual Fenland Poet Laureate awards were instigated for poets in the North of the county in 2012 at Wisbech & Fenland Museum.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The county was visited by travelling companies of comedians in the Georgian period.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The Lincoln Circuit included, at various times, Wisbech and Whittlesey.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The Wisbech Georgian theatre still survives as an operating theatre now known as The Angles Theatre.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] In Cambridge the ADC Theatre is the venue for the Footlights.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The county is covered by BBC East and ITV Anglia.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] Local radio includes BBC Radio Cambridgeshire, Greatest Hits Radio East, Heart East, Smooth East Midlands (only covering Peterborough), and Star Radio.
[src:a-tour-thro-the-whole-island-of-great-britain/cambridgeshire] The community radio stations are Black Cat Radio in St Neots; Cam FM and Cambridge 105 in Cambridge; Huntingdon Community Radio; and Peterborough Community Radio and Salaam Radio in Peterborough.
